## Summary
Handles the execution of the '/redo' command for world editing, allowing users to reapply their last undone change.

## Explanation
The chunk defines a command handler for the '/redo' world editing command. The `description` constant specifies that the command is used to 'Redo last change done to world with world editing commands.' The `usage` constant indicates that the command syntax is '/redo'. The `Args` struct is empty, meaning the command does not require any arguments.

The `execute` function checks if there is an action available in the redo history. If an action exists, it captures the current state as an undo blueprint using `Blueprint.capture`, reapplies the last change using `action.blueprint.paste`, and updates the undo history with the new blueprint. If no action is available, it informs the user that there is nothing to redo.

If an error occurs during the capture of the undo history, an error message '#ff0000Error: Could not capture undo history.' is sent to the user. After successfully redone an action, a success message '#00ff00Re-done last {s}.' is sent, where `{s}` is replaced by the action's message.

## Code Example
```zig
pub fn execute(_: Args, source: *User) void {
	if (source.worldEditData.redoHistory.pop()) |action| {
		defer action.deinit();

		const undo = Blueprint.capture(main.globalAllocator, action.selection());
		action.blueprint.paste(action.position, .{.preserveVoid = true});

		switch (undo) {
			.success => |blueprint| {
				source.worldEditData.undoHistory.push(.init(blueprint, action.position, action.message));
			},
			.failure => {
				source.sendMessage("#ff0000Error: Could not capture undo history.", .{});
			},
		}
		source.sendMessage("#00ff00Re-done last {s}.", .{action.message});
	} else {
		source.sendMessage("#ccccccNothing to redo.", .{});
	}
}
```

